\section{Describing tutorial steps}

Each step needs enough information for two different readers.
The student needs a title and instructions, while the runner needs a
small, explicit check that tells it whether the student can move on.

The step also needs one small interaction choice.  Most steps still open
an interactive shell, but some tasks are clearer in an editor.  An
optional file path is enough to distinguish those editor-backed steps
without introducing a larger action language in the first release.

The student-facing prose is still stored as plain strings, but we author
those strings as Markdown.  That gives the CLI room to render short
paragraphs and inline commands without inventing a larger tutorial markup
format in the first release.

We support two complementary checks:
\begin{description}
\item[Recorded-text patterns] small checks that should match the saved
  text for the step, whether that text came from a shell session or from
  an edited file.  Most are still plain strings, but some steps may need
  an explicit regular expression.
\item[Shell checks] a shell command that must succeed in the step
  workspace.
\end{description}

The combination stays simple but covers the first release well.  Some
steps are best recognised from what the student typed, while others are
best recognised from the files they created.

Plain strings remain the default because they are easy to author and read.
The runner can still treat those strings a little more forgivingly than a
raw byte-for-byte substring check by collapsing whitespace and removing
shell control noise.  That avoids brittle failures from harmless prompt or
completion variations while keeping the tutorial authoring format small.

When a step genuinely needs more control, we also allow an explicit match
mode in the form of a small mapping.  That keeps regular expressions
available without forcing every tutorial author to write them.

<<classes>>=
@dataclass(frozen=True)
class TextMatch:
    """One recorded-text check for a tutorial step."""

    pattern: str
    mode: str = "contains"
@

<<classes>>=
@dataclass(frozen=True)
class TutorialStep:
    """One interactive step in a tutorial."""

    title: str
    instructions: str
    required_patterns: tuple[TextMatch, ...] = ()
    check_command: str | None = None
    hint: str | None = None
    edit_file: str | None = None
@

Let's verify that a step can carry both transcript checks and a shell
check.

<<test functions>>=
def test_tutorial_step_keeps_validation_rules():
    step = TutorialStep(
        title="Create a file",
        instructions="Create notes.txt.",
        required_patterns=(TextMatch("notes.txt"),),
        check_command="test -f notes.txt",
    )

    assert step.required_patterns == (TextMatch("notes.txt"),)
    assert step.check_command == "test -f notes.txt"


def test_tutorial_step_can_request_editor_file():
    step = TutorialStep(
        title="Edit a file",
        instructions="Open notes.txt and update it.",
        edit_file="notes.txt",
    )

    assert step.edit_file == "notes.txt"
@


\section{Describing tutorials}

The tutorial object groups steps under a stable identifier.  The stable
identifier matters because progress is stored on disk, and the CLI needs
an ID that remains valid even if the prose title is revised later.

We also keep a small amount of source metadata.  That metadata lets the
runner detect when an unfinished tutorial changed on disk and refuse to
resume a run against a different definition.

<<classes>>=
@dataclass(frozen=True)
class Tutorial:
    """One loaded tutorial definition."""

    id: str
    title: str
    summary: str
    steps: tuple[TutorialStep, ...]
    source_path: str | None = None
    source_digest: str | None = None
@

<<test functions>>=
def test_tutorial_groups_steps_under_stable_id():
    tutorial = Tutorial(
        id="demo",
        title="Demo",
        summary="A short tutorial.",
        steps=(TutorialStep(title="One", instructions="Do it."),),
        source_path="/tmp/demo.md",
        source_digest="digest",
    )

    assert tutorial.id == "demo"
    assert tutorial.steps[0].title == "One"
    assert tutorial.source_digest == "digest"
@


\section{Recording step transcripts}

Review only works if we keep the text the student produced, and progress
tracking is more useful when it records whether the step was judged
complete.  A transcript therefore captures the recorded text for the
step, the exit status, and a boolean completion flag.

Shell steps save the visible shell transcript.  Editor steps instead save
the edited file contents and remember which file that text came from.
That keeps review small while still making editor-backed steps readable
after the original workspace changes.

<<classes>>=
@dataclass
class StepTranscript:
    """Recorded transcript for one tutorial step."""

    tutorial_id: str
    step_index: int
    title: str
    started_at: str
    ended_at: str
    exit_status: int
    transcript: str
    passed: bool = False
    edited_file: str | None = None
@

<<test functions>>=
def test_step_transcript_defaults_to_not_passed():
    transcript = StepTranscript(
        tutorial_id="demo",
        step_index=0,
        title="One",
        started_at="2026-01-01T00:00:00+00:00",
        ended_at="2026-01-01T00:00:01+00:00",
        exit_status=0,
        transcript="pwd\r\n",
    )

    assert transcript.passed is False


def test_step_transcript_can_store_edited_file_label():
    transcript = StepTranscript(
        tutorial_id="demo",
        step_index=0,
        title="Edit notes",
        started_at="2026-01-01T00:00:00+00:00",
        ended_at="2026-01-01T00:00:01+00:00",
        exit_status=0,
        transcript="tutorial basics\n",
        edited_file="notes.txt",
    )

    assert transcript.edited_file == "notes.txt"
@


\section{Recording tutorial runs}

Progress and review need a stable run record.  The run ID lets us resume
an unfinished session, while the workspace path tells later steps where
their files live.

The run also stores a copy of the tutorial title and source metadata.
That matters because review should still work even if the original
tutorial file has been moved or deleted later.

<<classes>>=
@dataclass
class TutorialRun:
    """Recorded run of a tutorial."""

    tutorial_id: str
    run_id: str
    workspace: str
    started_at: str
    updated_at: str
    tutorial_title: str | None = None
    tutorial_source_path: str | None = None
    tutorial_source_digest: str | None = None
    transcripts: list[StepTranscript] = field(default_factory=list)
@

<<test functions>>=
def test_tutorial_run_starts_with_empty_transcript_list():
    run = TutorialRun(
        tutorial_id="demo",
        tutorial_title="Demo",
        run_id="run-1",
        workspace="/tmp/demo",
        started_at="2026-01-01T00:00:00+00:00",
        updated_at="2026-01-01T00:00:00+00:00",
    )

    assert run.transcripts == []
    assert run.tutorial_title == "Demo"
